snippet.textDisplay:
I have been predicting for months that the US stock markets would peak by 25th March 2020 at the latest,
and that this would lose Trump the election because he has owned the stock markets rise,
so he must then own their fall.

I thought the most likely time they would peak was Oct 2019, that didnt happen, they also have gone above the peaks I predicted,

my prediction had been the Dow Jones would peak at 28000 and then fall to 14000,
in fact it has peaked around 29500, so I wasnt far off, and its now well below the peak I predicted,

I predicted the S&P 500 would peak at 3000 and fall to 1500,
in fact it has peaked around 3395, and is now below the peak I predicted,

I predicted the Nasdaq 100 would peak around 8000 and fall to 4000,
in fact it has peaked around 9730, and at the moment has only momentarily reached 8000,
will it descend below 8000?

I predicted all these peaks would occur by 25th March, 2020, with no timeline for the lows, as I expect that to take months,

I also predicted that the aforementioned peaks would only be outdone for a small window of time or quantity,

with the Dow Jones, the prediction was in fact outdone for more than 2 months.

I dont think anyone can predict exactly, so I think its quite a good prediction, in fact I was a bit surprised by the sudden drop as I was starting to think my prediction was wrong!

This prediction is based on 2 specific yield curves inverting before March 25th, 2019, that particular inversion has predicted the last 7 recessions.

the official definition of a recession is GDP falling for 2 quarters, but I use the word in a more general and vague way, meaning the economy going bad variously. So eg if the stock market peaks and begins a downward trend, for me that is a recession.

if in town you see a lot of companies going bankrupt, that is a recession.

if a lot of companies on the stock exchange declare bad results, that is a recession,

Saying recession is GDP falling for 2 quarters is just an attempt to make the idea precise, and is flawed anyway, because as things become more efficient and cheaper to produce, GDP falls.

so eg company A manufactures 1000 lightbulbs costing 1.1 each, its GDP is 1100.

but as it improves its processes, it can manufacture 2000 for 0.3 each, its GDP is now 600, the GDP has fallen, but the situation has improved, it is producing more lightbulbs for less money, can only be good, so its not a recession, its a procession!

so the definition based on GDP is flawed, its best to be vague about what a recession is.

For Trump, a recession is the stock market peaking, and beginning an aggressive downward trend.

I will leave my original prediction of the lows in place, as I think they will be reasonably good.

in fact because the peaks I mentioned were outdone, that means the falls will be all the more spectacular as the US stock exchanges are in a huge bubble.

these things cannot be changed by interest rates, lowering interest rates just makes the eventual fall all the more spectacular.

the only healthy way forwards is to RAISE interest rates, which in fact the fed were starting to do, but Trump forced them to lower rates, which they did, and now the consequences are emerging.
